{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "MarineAerosol",
        "description": "ModelingToolkit implementation of the Marine atmospheric aerosol size distribution, from Seinfeld & Pandis (2006), Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 2nd ed., Chapter 8 (\"Properties of the Atmospheric Aerosol\"), Table 8.3. The Marine distribution is a preset of the multi-modal lognormal AerosolDistribution model: three lognormal modes (N = [133, 66.6, 3.1] cm^-3, D_g = [0.008, 0.266, 0.580] um, log10 sigma = [0.657, 0.210, 0.396]) — a dilute marine boundary-layer background with a nucleation mode, an accumulation mode, and a coarse mode at 0.58 um. The model represents the aerosol number, surface-area and volume distributions as a sum of the three modes (Eq. 8.54) and reports the total number/surface/volume concentrations, the mode-1 Hatch-Choate diameters, and the vertical aerosol mass profile (Eq. 8.55). Migrated from Aerosol.jl MarineAerosol, a preset wrapper around AerosolDistribution(3). Purely algebraic: ten observed outputs, no differential states, an empty equations array. The upstream length-n_modes array parameters are scalarized at n_modes = 3 with the Marine Table 8.3 mode parameters as defaults.",
        "tags": [
            "aerosol",
            "size-distribution",
            "lognormal",
            "marine",
            "seinfeld_pandis_ch8"
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "MarineAerosol": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition, John Wiley & Sons, Chapter 8, \"Properties of the Atmospheric Aerosol\". Multi-modal lognormal size distribution: Eq. 8.54 (number), 8.49/8.50 (surface area), 8.52/8.53 (volume); Hatch-Choate diameters Eq. 8.44/8.50/8.53; total moments Eq. 8.41 with Eq. 8.5/8.7; vertical mass profile Eq. 8.55. Mode parameters are the Marine entry of Table 8.3.",
                "notes": "source_ref: Aerosol.jl@c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1:src/size_distribution.jl:182\n\nUpstream `MarineAerosol(; name=:MarineAerosol)` is a thin preset wrapper that calls `AerosolDistribution(3; name, N_vals, D_g_vals, logsigma_vals)` with the Marine mode parameters of Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3. It returns a flat MTK `System` — not a hierarchical composition — identical in structure to the base `AerosolDistribution` component but with the three array `@parameters` N / D_g / logsigma defaulted to the Marine values. The migration is therefore a standalone copy of `components/aerosol/size/aerosol_distribution.esm` with the nine scalarized mode-parameter defaults replaced; the ten observed-output expressions and the empty equations array are unchanged.\n\nMigration form: observed-form, matching `aerosol_distribution.esm`. The base component carries two `@constants` (pi_c = pi, ln10 = log(10)), the length-n_modes array `@parameters` N / D_g / logsigma plus the scalar `@parameters` D_p, z, H_p, and ten time-indexed `@variables` (n_N_o, n_S_o, n_V_o, N_t, S_t, V_t, D_s, D_v, D_bar, M_z) each defined by one algebraic `lhs ~ rhs` equation whose RHS references only parameters and constants. Per the purely-algebraic migration rule each output is encoded as `type: observed` with its defining relation in the `expression` field and the `equations` array is empty.\n\nArray scalarization: as in the base migration the length-3 array parameters N, D_g, logsigma are scalarized into nine scalar parameters N_1..N_3, D_g_1..D_g_3, logsigma_1..logsigma_3 and each `sum(... for i in 1:n_modes)` is unrolled into an explicit three-term sum. MarineAerosol is a three-mode distribution, so n_modes = 3 is exact (not a default truncation). The `.esm` array-variable path emits `getindex` nodes (tracked upstream as gt-p3ep), which is why the scalarized form is used.\n\nMarine defaults (Table 8.3, Seinfeld & Pandis 2006, Chapter 8): N = [133, 66.6, 3.1] cm^-3 -> [133e6, 66.6e6, 3.1e6] m^-3 (x1e6); D_g = [0.008, 0.266, 0.580] um -> [8e-9, 2.66e-7, 5.8e-7] m (x1e-6); logsigma = [0.657, 0.210, 0.396] (log10 of the geometric standard deviation, dimensionless). Mode 1 is a nucleation (Aitken) mode (D_g = 0.008 um, N = 133 cm^-3); mode 2 is an accumulation mode (D_g = 0.266 um, N = 66.6 cm^-3); mode 3 is a coarse mode (D_g = 0.580 um, N = 3.1 cm^-3). The marine aerosol is far more dilute than the Urban default: N_t = (133+66.6+3.1)e6 = 2.027e8 m^-3. D_p defaults to 1.0e-7 m (0.1 um) — the evaluation diameter used by the upstream test suite, consistent with `aerosol_distribution.esm`; z = 0 and H_p = 1000 m are the upstream scalar defaults.\n\nConstant handling: pi_c and ln10 are upstream `@constants`. The ESS schema has no constant variable type, so each migrates as a `type: parameter` with a fixed evaluated numeric default (pi_c = 3.141592653589793, ln10 = 2.302585092994046); the symbols are kept in the expressions. ln10 converts the log10-based logsigma to natural-log form: ln(sigma_g) = logsigma * ln10.\n\nPruned parameter: the base component's `@parameter rho_p` (particle density, default 1500 kg/m^3) appears in none of the ten equations and is omitted per the unused-parameter rule, as in `aerosol_distribution.esm`.\n\nTests: marine_default_distribution pins all ten outputs at the Marine defaults (D_p = 1.0e-7 m). The remaining six tests are the preset-independent equation-correctness tests carried over verbatim from `aerosol_distribution.esm` — they override the mode parameters (a single mode with modes 2 & 3 switched off, the lognormal one-sigma points, the near-monodisperse Hatch-Choate limit) or the vertical-profile parameters, so their expected values do not depend on the Marine defaults and verify the migrated equations directly. The Urban/Marine/Remote-continental preset-override tests of the base file are dropped — the Marine override case is reproduced here as the default-parameter test, and the Urban and Remote-continental cases are off-topic for this preset.\n\nNote on mode-1 Hatch-Choate diameters: D_s, D_v, D_bar are computed for mode 1 (nucleation mode). Mode 1 has a very wide distribution (logσ_1 = 0.657) so the Hatch-Choate diameters diverge substantially from D_g_1: the exp(k*ln^2 sigma) factors are much larger than for the Remote-continental mode 1 (logσ_1 = 0.161). This is reflected in the marine_default_distribution expected values where D_s >> D_g_1 and D_v >> D_s.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-9): the component is purely algebraic with no ODE integration. Each output is a finite composition of +, *, /, ^, sqrt, exp and log10 in float64 (round-off ~1e-16 relative); rel=1e-9 leaves seven orders of magnitude of headroom and absorbs any associativity difference in the n-ary sums. The marine_default_distribution expected values were generated with the canonical ESS Python runner (earthsci_toolkit.simulate) — the same pathway as the inline-test gate. The marine_default_distribution reference variable replaces `remote_continental_default_distribution`.\n\nUnits: descriptive only; the ESS runners do no dimensional analysis. Units are copied from the upstream `unit` metadata verbatim (n_S_o / S_t in m^-1, n_V_o / V_t / M_z dimensionless)."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-09
            },
            "variables": {
                "π_c": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 3.141592653589793,
                    "description": "Pi (mathematical constant). Upstream MTK @constants entry pi_c = pi; the ESS schema has no constant variable type, so it migrates as a fixed-default parameter with the evaluated numeric value."
                },
                "ln10": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 2.302585092994046,
                    "description": "Natural logarithm of 10. Upstream MTK @constants entry ln10 = log(10.0); migrated as a fixed-default parameter. Converts the log10-based geometric standard deviations logsigma to natural-log form, ln(sigma_g) = logsigma * ln10."
                },
                "N_1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 133000000.0,
                    "description": "Total number concentration of mode 1 (nucleation mode). Upstream array @parameter N[1] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Marine distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (133 cm^-3 converted to m^-3 by x1e6)."
                },
                "N_2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 66600000.0,
                    "description": "Total number concentration of mode 2 (accumulation mode). Upstream array @parameter N[2] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Marine distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (66.6 cm^-3 converted to m^-3 by x1e6)."
                },
                "N_3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 3100000.0,
                    "description": "Total number concentration of mode 3 (coarse mode). Upstream array @parameter N[3] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Marine distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (3.1 cm^-3 converted to m^-3 by x1e6)."
                },
                "D_g_1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 8e-09,
                    "description": "Geometric median diameter of mode 1 (nucleation mode). Upstream array @parameter D_g[1] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Marine distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (0.008 um converted to m by x1e-6)."
                },
                "D_g_2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 2.66e-07,
                    "description": "Geometric median diameter of mode 2 (accumulation mode). Upstream array @parameter D_g[2] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Marine distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (0.266 um converted to m by x1e-6)."
                },
                "D_g_3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 5.8e-07,
                    "description": "Geometric median diameter of mode 3 (coarse mode). Upstream array @parameter D_g[3] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Marine distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3 (0.580 um converted to m by x1e-6)."
                },
                "logσ_1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.657,
                    "description": "Log10 of the geometric standard deviation of mode 1 (nucleation mode) (dimensionless). Upstream array @parameter logσ[1] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Marine distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "logσ_2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.21,
                    "description": "Log10 of the geometric standard deviation of mode 2 (accumulation mode) (dimensionless). Upstream array @parameter logσ[2] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Marine distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "logσ_3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.396,
                    "description": "Log10 of the geometric standard deviation of mode 3 (coarse mode) (dimensionless). Upstream array @parameter logσ[3] of AerosolDistribution. Default: Marine distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "D_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1e-07,
                    "description": "Particle diameter at which the number, surface-area and volume distribution densities n_N_o/n_S_o/n_V_o are evaluated. The upstream base AerosolDistribution declares D_p with no default; 1.0e-7 m (0.1 um) is adopted here — the diameter the upstream test suite evaluates the distributions at, in the accumulation-mode range."
                },
                "z": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Altitude above the surface, used by the vertical mass profile M_z. Default 0 m (surface). Upstream @parameter z = 0.0."
                },
                "H_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1000.0,
                    "description": "Aerosol mass scale height in the vertical profile M_z = exp(-z/H_p). Default 1000 m. Upstream @parameter H_p = 1000.0."
                },
                "n_N_o": {
                    "type": "observed",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "description": "Number distribution density dN/d(log D_p) at the evaluation diameter D_p — the sum of n_modes lognormal modes (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006, Eq. 8.54).",
                    "expression": {
                        "op": "+",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "/",
                                        "args": [
                                            "N_1",
                                            {
                                                "op": "*",
                                                "args": [
                                                    {
                                                        "op": "sqrt",
                                                        "args": [
                                                            {
                                                                "op": "*",
                                                                "args": [
                                                                    2,
                                                                    "π_c"
                                                                ]
                                                            }
                                                        ]
                                                    },
                                                    "logσ_1"
                                                ]
                                            }
                                        ]
                                    },
                                    {
